\b \cf0 Digital Potlatch
\b0 \
Joaquin Rodriguez\
www.madrimasd.org/blogs/futurosdellibro\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\i \cf0 The Wikipedia Editor Survey 2011 emphasized\'a0 the importance of explicit acknowledgement and recognition of effort\'a0 among Wikipedia editors as an instrumental factor to sustain and grow\'a0 its community over the next years:\'a0
\i0 \

\i "Positive Reinforcement: Acknowledging the effort of editors is\'a0 important to reverse the editor decline. It is a commonly held view that\'a0 editors just want to see their articles improve and read by lots of\'a0 people and they don\'92t care about the opinion of their peers. This is\'a0 false. The survey finds that acknowledgement of peers via a nice note or\'a0 a barnstar (or kitten) is valued even more highly than achieving\'a0 featured article status. To sustain and grow our community, we need to\'a0 provide each other with positive feedback, and we should create tools to\'a0 make it easy to do so."\'a0
\i0 \

\i Participation in Internet communities has been a fascinating topic for\'a0 researchers, practitioners and members of these communities. A previous\'a0 study by Michlmayr, Robles and Gonz\'e1lez-Barahona showed evidence of\'a0 lasting volunteer participation in Debian. In this work, they defined\'a0 the half-life of contributors as the \'93the time required for a certain\'a0 population of maintainers to fall to half of its initial size\'94. In other\'a0 words, after 7.5 years of project evolution we can still find 50% of\'a0 the initial Debian maintainers participating in the project.\'a0
\i0 \

\i Our study on the inequality of contributions to Wikipedia shows that the\'a0 balance between casual and very active contributors has remained stable\'a0 for many years. Even more interesting is the fact that this balance did\'a0 not show any variation from 2007 onwards, despite the well-known\'a0 \'93plateau effect\'94 in the monthly number of edits to the largest\'a0 Wikipedias starting that year. What makes participants stay in online\'a0 communities? What factors motivate them to contribute? Why do they stop\'a0 participating? Our book \'93El Potlatch Digital: Wikipedia y el Triunfo del\'a0 Procom\'fan y el Conocimiento Compartido\'94 ["The Digital Potlatch:\'a0 Wikipedia and the Triumph of Commons and Shared Knowledge"], written\'a0 with Felipe Ortega, is an attempt to shed some light on this, mixing\'a0 empirical results with qualitative investigations.\'a0
\i0 \

\i Meritocracy and effort recognition has a central role in the motivation\'a0 of contributors in collaborative habitats like Wikipedia. This resembles\'a0 the Potlatch, an example that let us understand how in certain contexts\'a0 we need to give away our capital (material or intangible) so that the\'a0 community can give it back to us as acknowledgement, recognition and\'a0 reputation. As a result, in these collaborative habitats the working\'a0 capital does not have a monetary but a symbolic nature, and the logic of\'a0 its accumulation demands unselfishness to create another form of social\'a0 value. We don\'92t claim that this example is valid for all kind of\'a0 Internet communities, but some of the best-known cases (such as\'a0 Wikipedia) exemplify the triumph of shared knowledge and Commons over\'a0 other individualistic strategies.\'a0
\i0 \
\

\i Joaqu\'edn Rodr\'edguez has a PhD in geography and history (cultural\'a0 anthropology) and works as Professor in the area of Digital Society at\'a0 the University of Art and Digital Technology (U-Tad) of Camilo Jos\'e9\'a0 Cela. He is also Associate Professor of Technology and Society at the\'a0 Faculty of Philosophy at the Universidad Complutense in Madrid.\'a0 Rodr\'edguez is the author of several books related to publishing and\'a0 digital culture and economy, notably: El potlatch digital. Wikipedia y\'a0 el triunfo del procom\'fan y el conocimiento compartido (2011); El\'a0 paradigma digital y sostenible del libro (2011) and \'a1Todos sabios!\'a0 Ciencia ciudadana y conocimiento expandido (2013).
\i0 \
