\b \cf0 The Internet and its Parasites: Freedom and Participation
\b0 \
Chris Kelty\
kelty.org\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\i \cf0 The\'a0 two concepts of freedom and\'a0 participation have been central to the\'a0 social, cultural and\'a0 technological development of the Internet over the\'a0 last two decades.\'a0\'a0 From free software to open source, from\'a0 crowdsourcing to peer-to-peer\'a0 production, from fan fiction to\'a0 user-generated content, the concepts of\'a0 freedom and participation\'a0 justify a bewildering array of activities and\'a0 projects.\'a0 At the same\'a0 time, the concepts themselves are reshaped by new\'a0 practices and\'a0 technologies, sometimes ideologically, sometimes to make\'a0 sense of the\'a0 practical challenges created by new technologies in a\'a0 changing\'a0 political economy and global culture.\'a0 In this talk I will\'a0 discuss how\'a0 freedom and participation as concepts can be understood as\'a0 guides to\'a0 new technological practices, and how some kinds of projects\'a0 succeed and\'a0 others fail with respect to them.\'a0
\i0 \
\

\i Christopher\'a0 M. Kelty is an associate professor at the University of\'a0 California,\'a0 Los Angeles. He has a joint appointment in the Center for\'a0 Society and\'a0 Genetics, the department of Information Studies and the\'a0 Department of\'a0 Anthropology. His research focuses on the cultural\'a0 significance of\'a0 information technology, especially in science and\'a0 engineering. He is\'a0 the author most recently of Two Bits: The Cultural\'a0 Significance of Free\'a0 Software (Duke University Press, 2008), as well as\'a0 numerous articles\'a0 on open source and free software, including its impact\'a0 on education,\'a0 nanotechnology, the life sciences, and issues of peer\'a0 review and\'a0 research process in the sciences and in the humanities.
